The '''Solomon Bublick Award''' ('''Solomon Bublick Public Service Award''' or '''Solomon Bublick Prize''') is an award made by the [[Hebrew University of Jerusalem]] to a person who has made an important contribution to the advancement and development of the State of Israel. It has been called "Israel's Highest Award".{{r|CJC}} The first award was made in 1949.

==History==
Solomon Bublick (died 1945) was an [[United States|American]] who left the sum of $37,000 to establish the award to be granted every two years. It is one of the two prestigious awards made by the University.  The prize is given for a lifetime dedicated to the well-being of the Jewish people and the State of Israel, alternatively to an Israeli and to a personality from abroad.{{r|HU1}}

In 1950, the award included $1500.{{r|JTA1}}
In 1960, the award included a sterling silver plaque and $1000.{{r|JTA2}}

